{"meta":{"spec_version":"0.3","created":"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z","author":"OpenChronology Demo"},"event":{"id":"charlemagne-coronation-800","type":"event","content":{"title":"Coronation of Charlemagne","date_label":"December 25, 800 CE","description":"On **Christmas Day, 800 CE**, Pope Leo III crowned **Charles I of the Franks** — Charlemagne — as *\"Emperor of the Romans\"* in St. Peter's Basilica in Rome, reviving the Roman imperial title in the West for the first time in over three centuries.\n\nCharlemagne had already unified most of Western Europe through decades of military campaigns. His coronation represented a political and symbolic fusion of Roman tradition, Frankish power, and Christian authority that would define European political culture for centuries.\n\nThe **Carolingian Renaissance** he sponsored revived Latin learning, standardized the church liturgy, and established palace schools that preserved classical texts. Charlemagne is often called the *\"Father of Europe\"* — the architect of a civilizational vision that shaped the continent long after his empire fragmented among his grandsons.","description_format":"markdown","tags":["charlemagne","carolingian","papal","coronation","frankish","800"],"sources":[{"title":"Charlemagne — Encyclopedia Britannica","url":"https://www.britannica.com/biography/Charlemagne"}]},"temporal":{"calendar":"gregorian","start_value":"800","precision":"year"},"significance":{"value":910,"temporal_scope":"centuries","geographic_scope":"western-europe"}}}
